Impact of the us of synthetic data in IPD Meta-Analysis: A simulation study

metaConvert team

2025-06-06

1. Methods

1.1 Synthetic data generation

A predetermined proportion of studies (0%, 33%, 66%, 100%) had their original (true) IPD replaced with synthetic versions. This was performed by the synthpop R package.

Synthesis method: A parametric approach (synthesis_method = parametric) was employed. synthpop dynamically selected synthesis routines based on variable type (e.g., norm for numeric, logreg for binary, polyreg for categorical factors, sample as a fallback).

For each study whose data was synthesized, m=50 independent synthetic datasets will be generated.

1.2 Meta-analysis model

A one-stage IPD meta-analysis using a linear mixed-effects model was used to estimate the treatment effect. The model specification was: outcome ~ treatment01 + cont_cov + num2_cont_cov + bin_cov01 + multi_cov + (1 + treatment01 | study_id)

This model estimates the overall treatment effect while accounting for covariates and allowing for study-specific random intercepts and random slopes for the treatment effect. If this complex model failed to converge (I provide below the rate of convergence/warnings), a simpler model with only random intercepts was attempted: outcome ~ treatment01 + cont_cov + num2_cont_cov + bin_cov01 + multi_cov + (1 | study_id)

1.3 Multiple imputations

When analyzing datasets containing synthetic data (prop_synthetic > 0), the m=50 meta-analysis results were pooled using Rubins Rules. A single pooled treatment effect estimate, its standard error, and associated statistics, properly accounting for both within-imputation and between-imputation variance was generated.

1.4 Simulation scenarios

The simulation study explored a comprehensive grid of scenarios. Each unique combination of the following parameters constituted a distinct scenario :

  • Number of studies (n_studies): k=10,20,50,100 ?
  • Number of individuals per study (n_per_study): n=20, 50, 100, 500 ? (which variance ?)
  • True treatment effect (SMD; treatment_effect): SMD=0, 0.2, 0.5, 0.8 ?
  • Between-study variance for treatment (tau_squared): tau=0.1, 0.3, 0.5 ?
  • within-study variance for treatment (sigma_squared): s=1 ?
  • Proportion of synthetic studies (prop_synthetic): p=0, 0.33, 0.66, 1 ?
  • Number of multiple imputations for synthetic data (m_value): m=50 ?
  • Covariates ?
    • treatment<->covariates association magnitude/SD: ??
    • outcome<->covariates association magnitude/SD: ??
    • covariates<->covariates association magnitude/SD: ??

1.5 Performance Metrics

Effect

  • bias_mean: Average difference between the synthetic estimate and the true treatment effect.
  • bias_median: Median difference.
  • rel_bias_mean_perc: Mean bias as a percentage of the true effect.

Overall

  • RMSE: Root Mean Squared Error, combining bias and variability.

Variance

  • avg_variance_ratio: Average ratio of synthetic analysis variance to all-real data analysis variance.

95% CI

  • avg_ci_width_ratio: Average ratio of synthetic CI width to all-real data CI width.
  • coverage_synth: Proportion of 95% CIs from synthetic analysis containing the true treatment effect.

Heterogeneity Estimation

  • bias_tau2_mean: Mean bias in the estimation of tau_squared (treatment effect heterogeneity).
